---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
---

<Layout
    title="Data Vizes with Bricks | tcplot: Data Visualization in Minneapolis and St. Paul"
    description="A hands-on morning building data visualizations out of LEGO — bring your own dataset or use one of ours."
>
    <div class="max-w-6xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-8">
        <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto mt-8 mb-12">
            <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">
                Upcoming: Data Vizes with Bricks — October 3rd
            </h2>

            <div class="mb-6 text-gray-700">
                <p class="text-lg font-semibold text-gray-900">
                    Saturday, Oct 3 · 10:00 AM to 12:00 PM CDT
                </p>
                <p class="flex items-start gap-2 mt-1">
                    <svg
                        class="w-5 h-5 mt-0.5 shrink-0 text-gray-400"
                        viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                        fill="currentColor"
                        aria-hidden="true"
                    >
                        <path
                            fill-rule="evenodd"
                            d="M12 2c-3.866 0-7 3.07-7 6.857 0 4.34 4.686 9.86 6.412 11.74a.8.8 0 0 0 1.176 0C14.314 18.717 19 13.197 19 8.857 19 5.07 15.866 2 12 2Zm0 9.5a2.5 2.5 0 1 1 0-5 2.5 2.5 0 0 1 0 5Z"
                            clip-rule="evenodd"></path>
                    </svg>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                            >The Coffee Shop NE</span
                        ><br />2852 Johnson St NE · Minneapolis, MN</span
                    >
                </p>
            </div>

            <p class="text-xl text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                What if a bar chart had studs?
            </p>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-4">
                Join <span class="font-silkscreen">tcplot</span> for a hands-on
                morning building data visualizations out of LEGO. Bricks are a
                weirdly perfect medium for data: they snap to a grid, they stack
                into bars, they come in fixed colors and sizes, and a 1×1 brick is
                a ready-made unit of one. We'll spend two hours turning small
                datasets into things you can stack, hold, and knock over.
            </p>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                The premise is simple: <strong>bring your own dataset or use one
                of ours, and build a data visualization with it.</strong> Pick
                something small, decide what's worth showing, and make it in
                bricks — solo or alongside whoever's at your table. You leave with
                a thing you built (and a much sharper eye for what makes an
                encoding work).
            </p>

            <div class="flex justify-center mt-12 mb-8">
                <div class="max-w-2xl w-full rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
                    <img
                        src="/images/lego-rainbow-mosaic.jpeg"
                        alt="A dense rainbow mosaic of LEGO bricks, plates, and flower pieces arranged in a gradient from red through green to blue and purple"
                        class="w-full h-auto object-contain"
                    />
                </div>
            </div>

            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
                What you'll do
            </h3>
            <ul class="space-y-3 text-gray-600 mb-8">
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                            >Pick a dataset.</span
                        > Bring your own — a week of your steps, a poll of your
                        friends, anything small — or grab one of the pre-prepared
                        datasets we'll have ready.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                            >Name the question.</span
                        > Decide the one thing you want it to show, and rough out an
                        encoding before you reach for the bricks.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900">Build it.</span> Make
                        your visualization in LEGO, solo or in a small group. We'll
                        circulate with prompts when you're stuck and more bricks when
                        you get ambitious.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900">Share.</span> Tell
                        the table what you encoded, what you left out, and what
                        surprised you when the data became something you could hold.</span
                    >
                </li>
            </ul>

            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
                How the two hours will flow
            </h3>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                A loose schedule — we'll bend it to the room. The point is that you
                walk in with a dataset and walk out with an object.
            </p>
            <ul class="space-y-3 text-gray-600 mb-8">
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                            >Welcome.</span
                        > Coffee, quick intros, and a dump of bricks on the table so
                        your hands have something to do while we talk.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900">Warm-up.</span> Everyone
                        picks a single brick for how they're feeling today and says
                        why in a sentence — a low-stakes way to meet the room and
                        start thinking of bricks as something that can carry meaning.
                        If we have enough of us, we'll snap them together into one
                        little build: our first dataset of the day, the mood of the
                        room.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                            >Encoding with bricks.</span
                        > A short crash course in the brick's vocabulary of data, and
                        a single dataset turned into a build live so you can see the
                        choices before you make your own.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                            >Pick &amp; sketch.</span
                        > Choose your dataset, name your one question, and rough out
                        the encoding on paper before you touch the bricks.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900">Build.</span> The
                        heart of it — make your visualization, solo or in pairs.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                            >Show &amp; tell.</span
                        > Walk the table through what everyone made, then a group photo
                        of all of it before the bricks go back in the bin.</span
                    >
                </li>
            </ul>

            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
                Encoding with bricks
            </h3>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                On a screen you reach for <em>x</em>, <em>y</em>, color, and
                size. A brick hands you a different — and oddly generous — set of
                channels, most of them already quantized into clean units:
            </p>
            <ul class="space-y-3 text-gray-600 mb-8">
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><strong>Height (stack count).</strong> The obvious one and
                        the strongest — a tower of <em>n</em> bricks is a bar of
                        exactly <em>n</em>. The eye and the fingers both count it.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><strong>Studs / footprint.</strong> A 2×4 is eight units of
                        area. Length and width encode magnitude without any stacking
                        at all.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><strong>Color.</strong> A fixed, nameable palette — perfect
                        for category, and the discipline of a limited set keeps you
                        honest.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><strong>Position on the baseplate.</strong> The grid is a
                        free coordinate system — rows, columns, small multiples, an
                        honest-to-goodness scatterplot.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><strong>Order &amp; spacing.</strong> Near and far, gaps
                        between towers, sequence along a row — time and rank for free.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><strong>Shape &amp; texture.</strong> Plates vs. bricks,
                        smooth tiles vs. studded tops, a slope, a transparent piece —
                        a second categorical channel when you've run out of colors.</span
                    >
                </li>
            </ul>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-8">
                The trade-off is the same as always: you can only encode a few
                variables before the build stops being legible, so choosing what to
                <em>leave out</em> is the real craft.
            </p>

            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
                Datasets to choose from
            </h3>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-8">
                No data of your own? We'll have a stack ready — small,
                self-contained, and brick-friendly. They run from one-category
                warm-ups (M&amp;M's by color, coffee cups by day) to multi-variable
                challenges (Olympic medal counts, the planets by size and distance),
                plus a few we can collect from the room on the spot (heights at the
                table, how everyone got here this morning). Bring your own and we'll
                make room for it.
            </p>

            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
                Want to make it a game?
            </h3>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                If your table wants a little friendly competition, there are a few
                quick games hiding in a pile of LEGO and a stack of datasets —
                totally optional, and easy to steal for your own group:
            </p>
            <ul class="space-y-3 text-gray-600 mb-8">
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                            >Brick to Brick.</span
                        > Our take on <em>Apples to Apples</em>: everyone encodes the
                        same small dataset on a short timer, a rotating judge picks
                        the build that reads best, and the winner keeps the card.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                            >Reverse charades.</span
                        > Someone builds a viz from a hidden dataset; the table races
                        to guess what the data <em>is</em>. If they can recover the
                        story, the encoding worked.</span
                    >
                </li>
                <li class="flex items-start gap-2">
                    <span class="mt-1 text-gray-400">&#x25B8;</span>
                    <span
                        ><span class="font-semibold text-gray-900"
                            >The collaborative mosaic.</span
                        > One big baseplate, one shared dataset (a poll of the room,
                        say). Everyone places a row until the wall is a heatmap we all
                        built together.</span
                    >
                </li>
            </ul>

            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
                What we'll provide
            </h3>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                LEGO — lots of it, sorted into shared bins — baseplates, paper and
                markers for sketching, and pre-prepared datasets ready to go. No
                need to bring your own bricks, though you're welcome to.
            </p>

            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
                What to bring
            </h3>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                Yourself. Optionally: a small dataset you'd like to build (a week of
                your own data, a poll of your friends, anything small), or a handful
                of distinctive bricks of your own to throw in the pile.
            </p>

            <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-gray-900 mb-3">
                Who this is for
            </h3>
            <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 leading-relaxed mb-6">
                Anyone curious about data visualization — practitioners working in
                D3, Tableau, ggplot2, Observable, or none of the above. Kids
                welcome!
            </p>
        </div>
    </div>
</Layout>
